  <h1>TDS on dividend under Section 194</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>5 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>Since dividends are taxable in the shareholder's hands, a company deducts TDS at 10% under Section 194 on dividends paid to a resident shareholder above the threshold (Rs.10,000 following the Finance Act 2025).</b> Without PAN, the rate is 20%; eligible shareholders can file Form 15G/15H to avoid deduction.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">The post-DDT position</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Rate, threshold and no-PAN</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Avoiding deduction</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Practical points</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">The post-DDT position</h2>
<p>After the abolition of dividend distribution tax, dividends are <b>taxable in the hands of shareholders</b> at their slab rate. To collect tax on this, the company paying the dividend deducts <b>10%</b> TDS under Section 194 (for residents) at the time of payment or distribution.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Rate, threshold and no-PAN</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Position</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Rate (resident)</td><td>10%</td></tr><tr><td>Threshold</td><td>Rs.10,000 per year [VERIFY] (raised by Finance Act 2025)</td></tr><tr><td>No PAN</td><td>20% (Section 206AA)</td></tr><tr><td>Non-resident shareholder</td><td>Section 195 / DTAA</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

  <h2 id="s2">Avoiding deduction</h2>
<p>A resident whose total income is below the taxable limit can submit <a href="form-15g-15h-tds-exemption.html">Form 15G (or 15H for senior citizens)</a> to the company for nil deduction. A <a href="lower-tds-certificate-section-197.html">Section 197 certificate</a> can also fix a lower rate.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">Practical points</h2>
<ul><li>For <b>non-resident</b> shareholders, dividend TDS is under <a href="tds-foreign-payments-section-195-dtaa.html">Section 195</a> at the treaty/Act rate with TRC.</li><li>Reconcile dividend TDS in <a href="form-26as-ais-tis-difference.html">Form 26AS/AIS</a>.</li><li>Report dividend income in the return even if below the TDS threshold.</li><li>Mutual-fund income distributions follow Section 194K.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is the TDS rate on dividends?</summary><p>10% under Section 194 for resident shareholders above the threshold; 20% if PAN is not furnished. Non-residents are covered by Section 195.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What is the threshold for dividend TDS?</summary><p>Around Rs.10,000 per year following the Finance Act 2025 (raised from Rs.5,000). Confirm the figure for the year.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How can I avoid TDS on dividends?</summary><p>If your total income is below the taxable limit, submit Form 15G or 15H to the company, or obtain a lower-deduction certificate under Section 197.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>Dividends taxable in shareholders' hands; company deducts 10% (194).</li><li>Threshold around Rs.10,000 (Finance Act 2025); 20% without PAN.</li><li>Non-residents: Section 195 with treaty relief.</li><li>Form 15G/15H or Section 197 can avoid/reduce deduction.</li></ul>
  </div>

